example.p:
Now consider the function
y &= \sin(x) & \text{with domain } -\frac{\pi}{2} \leq x \leq \frac{\pi}{2}
This function has the same formula but the domain has been restricted so that, as we'll now show, the horizontal line test is satisfied.

That is, for each -1\le Y \le 1, there is exactly one x, call it X, that obeys both
\sin X &= Y &\text{and} && -\frac{\pi}{2}\le X \le \frac{\pi}{2}
That unique value, X, is typically denoted \arcsin(Y). That is
\sin( \arcsin(Y) ) &= Y & \text{and} && -\frac{\pi}{2}\le \arcsin(Y) \le\frac{\pi}{2}
Renaming Y\rightarrow x, the inverse function \arcsin(x) is defined for all -1 \le x \le 1 and is determined by the equation

Since
\sin\frac{\pi}{2}=1\qquad\sin\frac{\pi}{6}=\frac{1}{2}
and -\frac{\pi}{2}\le \frac{\pi}{6},\frac{\pi}{2}\le \frac{\pi}{2}, we have
\arcsin 1= \frac{\pi}{2}\qquad \arcsin \frac{1}{2}= \frac{\pi}{6}
Even though
\sin(2\pi)=0
it is not true that \arcsin 0 =2\pi, and it is not true that \arcsin\big(\sin(2\pi)\big) =2\pi, because 2\pi is not between -\frac{\pi}{2} and \frac{\pi}{2}. More generally
\arcsin\big(\sin(x)\big) &=\text{ the unique angle } \theta \text{ between } -\frac{\pi}{2} \text{ and } \frac{\pi}{2} \text{ obeying } \sin \theta =\sin x
&= x\quad\text{if and only if $-\frac{\pi}{2}\le x\le \frac{\pi}{2}$}
So, for example, \arcsin\big(\sin\big(\frac{11\pi}{16}\big)\big) cannot be \frac{11\pi}{16} because \frac{11\pi}{16} is bigger than \frac{\pi}{2}. So how do we find the correct answer? Start by sketching the graph of \sin(x).

subsection.p:
Since \sin(\theta)=x (see ), we have made the side opposite the angle \theta of length x and the hypotenuse of length 1. Then, by Pythagoras, the side adjacent to \theta has length \sqrt{1-x^2} and so
\cos\big(\arcsin(x)\big)=\cos(\theta)=\sqrt{1-x^2}
which in turn gives us the answer we need:
\diff{}{x} \arcsin(x) =\frac{1}{\sqrt{1-x^2}}

statement.p:
\arcsin x is defined for |x|\le 1. It is the unique number obeying
\sin\big(\arcsin(x)\big)&=x &&\text{and}& -\frac{\pi}{2}\le &\arcsin(x)\le\frac{\pi}{2}
\arccos x is defined for |x|\le 1. It is the unique number obeying
\cos\big(\arccos(x)\big)&=x &&\text{and}& 0\le &\arccos(x)\le\pi
\arctan x is defined for all x\in\bbbr. It is the unique number obeying
\tan\big(\arctan(x)\big)&=x &&\text{and}& -\frac{\pi}{2} \lt &\arctan(x) \lt \frac{\pi}{2}
\arccsc x=\arcsin\frac{1}{x} is defined for |x|\ge 1. It is the unique number obeying \csc\big(\arccsc(x)\big)&=x &&\text{and}& -\frac{\pi}{2}\le &\arccsc(x)\le\frac{\pi}{2}
\arcsec x=\arccos\frac{1}{x} is defined for |x|\ge 1. It is the unique number obeying \sec\big(\arcsec(x)\big)&=x &&\text{and}& 0\le &\arcsec(x)\le\pi
\arccot x is defined for all x\in\bbbr. It is the unique number obeying \cot\big(\arccot(x)\big)&=x &&\text{and}& 0 \lt &\arccot(x) \lt \pi

example.p:
 To find the derivative of \arccsc we can use its definition and the chain rule.


  \theta &= \arccsc x & \text{take cosecant of both sides}

\csc \theta &= x & \text{but $\csc \theta = \frac{1}{\sin\theta}$, so flip both sides}

\sin \theta &= \frac{1}{x} & \text{now take arcsine of both sides}

  \theta &= \arcsin\left(\frac{1}{x}\right)


Now just differentiate, carefully using the chain rule :


  \diff{\theta}{x} &= \diff{}{x} \arcsin\left(\frac{1}{x}\right)

  &= \frac{1}{\sqrt{1-x^{-2}}} \cdot \frac{-1}{x^2}

To simplify further we will factor x^{-2} out of the square root. We need to
be a little careful doing that. Take another look at examples
and and the discussion between them before proceeding.
  &= \frac{1}{\sqrt{x^{-2}(x^2-1)}} \cdot \frac{-1}{x^2}

  &= \frac{1}{|x^{-1}|\cdot \sqrt{x^2-1}} \cdot \frac{-1}{x^2} & \text{note that $x^2 \cdot |x^{-1}| = |x|$.}

  &= - \frac{1}{|x|\sqrt{x^2-1}}

statement.p:
The derivatives of the inverse trigonometric functions are


\diff{}{x} \arcsin(x) &= \frac{1}{\sqrt{1-x^2}} &
\diff{}{x} \arccsc(x) &= -\frac{1}{|x|\sqrt{x^2-1}}

\diff{}{x} \arccos(x) &= -\frac{1}{\sqrt{1-x^2}} &
\diff{}{x} \arcsec(x) &= \frac{1}{|x|\sqrt{x^2-1}}

\diff{}{x} \arctan(x) &= \frac{1}{1+x^2} &
\diff{}{x} \arccot(x) &= -\frac{1}{1+x^2}
